1. Introduction:

Music has stayed relatively constant in our lives, and it surrounds us during different moments. We use it to push us to the limits during an intense workout, help us focus while studying in the library till 2am, and we even use music to let loose while partying with our friends! During happy, sad, celebratory and other moments in our lives, music has stayed by our side.

On March 11, 2020, WHO (World Health Organization) declared COVID-19 a global pandemic. A majority of our lives changed from this point on such as switching to virtual school, following a stay at home order, closing down indoor seating in restaurants, wearing masks and staying 6 feet apart from friends. With such a huge change in our lives, we wanted to study the impact of COVID-19 on music, and see if the top 2020 songs had any distinct features compared to the top songs of 2010-2019. Since COVID-19 is still occurring in our lives today, we will be studying the top songs pre-COVID-19 and during/the peak of COVID-19.

Along with many new rules and changes to what our normal looked like, there was one app that started to change our lives as well. That app was Tik Tok. Tik Tok is an app where people can post 30 second to 1 minute videos about anything the user wants to post. We believe Tik Tok impacted the music/top songs of 2020 since many songs go viral if someone choreographs catchy dance moves to a portion of a song. This is how some artists become very popular and sometimes get discovered! One example is Doja Cats song Say So where she even included the catchy Tik Tok dance in her official music video. Along with our assumptions that Tik Tok played an important role for the top songs of 2020, we also want to analyze the features of popular Tik Tok songs.

What we will analyze:

  • Top Songs of 2010-2019 vs. Top Songs of 2020 (impact of COVID-19)
  • TikTok Songs vs Top Songs of 2020
  • What makes a song popular

Required Tools/Libraries:¶

2. Data Collection & Processing¶

Obtaining Data:
The top songs of 2020 data was obtained from Organize Your Music using this Spotify Tops Songs of 2020 Playlist. The top songs of 2010-2019 data were used from this Kaggle dataset. The top Tik Tok songs was also obtained from Organize Your Music, but using this Spotify Tik Tok Songs. The website Organize Your Music is super cool since it is linked to your Spotify account where you can analyze your own Spotify playlists. Moreover, you can find a specific Spotify playlists URI (heres a Spotify playlist to URI converter that helped us) and analyze that playlist, which is what we did. This website already produced the following properties for each song on the playlist.

  • Genre - the genre of the track
  • Year - the release year of the recording.
  • Added - the earliest date you added the track to your collection.
  • Beats Per Minute (BPM) - The tempo of the song. Energy - The energy of a song - the higher the value, the more energetic. song
  • Danceability - The higher the value, the easier it is to dance to this song.
  • Loudness (dB) - The higher the value, the louder the song.
  • Liveness - The higher the value, the more likely the song is a live recording.
  • Valence - The higher the value, the more positive mood for the song.
  • Length - The duration of the song.
  • Acousticness - The higher the value the more acoustic the song is.
  • Speechiness - The higher the value the more spoken word the song contains.
  • Popularity - The higher the value the more popular the song is.

Tidying the Data:

The year added column of our data was not accurate since this date was the date I added the playlist to my Spotify account, so we removed this column. We also made sure all the column names for the datasets were the same. The dataset we first imported is the tops songs of 2010-2019, then we imported the top songs of 2020, and lastly we imported the top Tik Tok songs. We also created a dataset that combined the top songs of 2010-2019 and 2020, so we have a dataset that will carry the top songs of 2010-2020.

  • top_10s = top songs of 2010-2019
  • top_2020 = top songs of 2020
  • tiktok = the top Tik Tok songs
  • top_all = top songs of 2010-2020

#find the average value of each track property each year
df = top_all.copy()

track_properties = ['bpm','nrgy', 'dnce', 'dB',
                     'live', 'val', 'dur', 'acous', 'spch']

property_avgs = df.groupby(["year"])[track_properties].mean()
property_avgs.reset_index(inplace=True)

We can end backwards elimination here, as all variables have a p-value below 0.05.
